docs.abstract: Stocks fell more than 6 percent in May, as threats to the global economy seemed to proliferate by the week, with tariffs rising and talks yielding no meaningful results.

docs.lead_paragraph: Stocks began 2019 with the snappiest start in more than three decades, as the economy grew faster than expected, the Federal Reserve seemed to abandon its plans to keep raising interest rates, and trade-war rancor between Washington and Beijing seemed to end. By April 30, the S&P 500 had reached a record.

headline.main: Things Were Going Great for Wall Street. Then the Trade War Heated Up.
headline.print_headline: Giddy Streak in 2019 Ends as Trade Tweets Shatter Markets’ Calm

docs.lead_paragraph: SHANGHAI — Three days before the most sensitive political anniversary on the Chinese calendar, Twitter suspended the accounts of Chinese political commentators in what it said was an accident. docs.lead_paragraph: CHICAGO — The Federal Reserve chairman, Jerome H. Powell, said on Tuesday that the central bank was prepared to act to sustain the economic expansion if President Trump’s trade war weakened the economy. His remarks sent stocks soaring as investors predicted a cut in interest rates.

headline.main: Stocks Jump as Fed’s Powell Suggests Rates Could Come Down

docs.lead_paragraph: The Trump administration’s threat to impose new tariffs on nearly everything that comes to the United States from China has sent American retailers scrambling. Many rely on China for some portion of their manufacturing, and the new tariffs — as much as 25 percent on the roughly $300 billion worth of goods that so far have been untouched by the trade war — could force the companies to change where and how they make their products.

headline.main: How China Tariffs Could Make Your Sweaters and Pants Cost More
headline.print_headline: How Tariffs May Raise This Sweater’s Price
